Then, remove the exterior hardware (handles, lock cylinders, etc.). If you have difficulty removing the hardware, you may simply mask the hardware prior to painting. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4c/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/4/4c/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/aid5058633-v4-728px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The cabinet and drawers will have to be hand-sanded around any hardware that is left in place. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/3/38/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/aid5058633-v4-728px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

WD-40 and a razor blade work very well for this. Spray some WD-40 directly onto the sticker and let it stand for a few minutes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6c/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/6/6c/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/aid5058633-v4-728px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Then, carefully use a razor blade or something else that will scrape the sticker away. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/25/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/2/25/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/aid5058633-v4-728px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Wipe away the excess WD-40 with an old cloth or paper towel. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d1/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/d/d1/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/aid5058633-v4-728px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you are giving a wood cabinet a makeover, it is not recommended to sand and re-stain wood cabinets. This is because if the wood is thoroughly sealed, it will not absorb new stain very well. This will result in a blotchy finish. If you are simply applying a new clear coat, remove all exterior hardware and clean the cabinet and drawers by buffing with very fine steel wool. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/2/2b/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet2.jpg/aid5058633-v4-728px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Wipe away all the dust and follow the same procedure as painting metal cabinets. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b5/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/b/b5/Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet3.jpg/aid5058633-v4-728px-Give-a-File-Cabinet-a-Makeover-Step-28Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
